In [[paleolinguistics]], a '''Semitism''' is a grammatical or syntactical behaviour in a language which reveals that the influence of a [[Semitic language]] is present. The most common example is the influence of [[Aramaic]] on some texts written in [[Jewish Koine Greek]].<ref>Jonathan T. Pennington Heaven and Earth in the Gospel of Matthew - Page 105 - 2007 "This nuanced difference between a “Semitic enhancement” and a “Semitism” enables us to reconsider whether an apparent linguistic anomaly in Greek (such as plural) is truly a "Semitism" and not merely an "enhancement".</ref>
