'''Susan Ellen Alcock''' is an American [[archaeologist]] specialising in survey archaeology and the archaeology of memory in the provinces of the [[Roman Empire]]. Alcock grew up in [[Massachusetts]] and was educated at [[Yale]] and the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>https://vivo.brown.edu/display/salcock</ref> She is currently Special Counsel for Institutional Outreach and Engagement and Professor of Classical Archaeology and Classics at the University of Michigan and became the Interim [[Provost (education)|Provost]] and [[Vice-Chancellor|Vice Chancellor]] for Academic Affairs at the [[University of Michigan - Flint]] in July 2018.
{{Infobox academic|honorific_prefix=Professor|name=Susan E. Alcock|alma_mater=[[Yale University]], [[University of Cambridge]]|thesis_title=Greek society and the transition to Roman rule|discipline=Archaeology|sub_discipline=|workplaces=[[University of Michigan]], [[Brown University]], [[University of Michigan-Flint]]}}
==Early life and education== From 1979 to 1983, Alcock studied at [[Yale University]], graduating with a ''[[summa cum laude]]'' [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) degree which [[Major (academic)|majored]] in Archaeology and History. She then studied [[Classical Tripos|classics]] at the [[University of Cambridge]], graduating with a [[First Class Honours|first class]] BA in 1985; as per tradition, this BA was promoted to a [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Master of Arts]] (MA Cantab) degree in 1989.<ref name="CV">{{cite web|title=CURRICULUM VITAE: Susan E. Alcock|url=https://lsa.umich.edu/classics/people/departmental-faculty/susan-alcock/_jcr_content/file.res/Alcock_CV_September_2015.pdf|website=College of Literature, Science, and the Arts|publisher=University of Michigan|accessdate=8 July 2016|format=pdf|date=2015}}</ref> She remained at Cambridge to undertake [[postgraduate research]], and completed her [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (PhD) degree in 1989 with a [[doctoral thesis]] titled "Greek society and the transition to Roman rule".<ref name="CV" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Alcock|first1=Susan Ellen|title=Greek society and the transition to Roman rule|url=http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?did=8&uin=uk.bl.ethos.304193|website=E-Thesis Online Service|publisher=The British Library|accessdate=9 July 2016|date=1988}}</ref>
==Career== Alcock served as the Director of the [[Joukowsky Institute for Archaeology and the Ancient World]] and Professor of Classics at [[Brown University]] from January 2006 until 2015.<ref>[https://www.brown.edu/Departments/Joukowsky_Institute/about/Newsletters/JIAAWNewsletter-FallWinter2015.pdf ''Inventory: News from the Joukowsky Institute for Archaeology and the Ancient World'' Fall/Winter 2015]</ref> Prior to that, she was the John H. D'Arms Professor of Classical Archaeology at the [[University of Michigan]]. She was co-director of the [[Pylos Regional Archaeological Project]] in southwestern Greece, then co-director of the [[Vorotan Project]] in southern [[Armenia]], and is now director of the [[Brown University Petra Archaeological Project]]. In 2000<ref>https://www.macfound.org/fellows/class/july-2000/</ref> she was awarded a [[MacArthur Fellowship]].<ref>http://www.archaeology.org/0507/etc/conversations.html</ref>
In 2018 Alcock was appointed as the interim [[Provost (education)|provost]] and [[Vice-chancellor|vice chancellor]] for academic affairs at the [[University of Michigan–Flint|University of Michigan-Flint]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.umflint.edu/2018/06/21/susan-alcock-appointed-interim-provost-and-vice-chancellor-for-academic-affairs-at-um-flint/|title=Alcock appointed Interim Provost & VC for Academic Affairs at UM-Flint|date=2018-06-21|work=UM-Flint NOW|access-date=2018-06-22|language=en-US}}</ref>
==Publications== * ''Graecia Capta: The Landscapes of Roman Greece'' (Cambridge 1993) * (editor with Robin Osborne) ''Placing the Gods: Sanctuaries and Sacred Space in Ancient Greece'' (Oxford 1994) * (editor) ''The Early Roman Empire in the East'' (Oxford 1997) * ''Archaeologies of the Greek Past: Landscape, Monuments and Memory'' (Cambridge 2001) * (edited with John Cherry and [[Jas Elsner]]) ''Pausanias: Travel and Memory in Roman Greece'' (New York 2001) * (editor with Terence D'Altroy, Kathleen Morrison and Carla Sinopoli) ''Empires: Perspectives from History and Archaeology'' (Cambridge 2001) * (editor with Ruth Van Dyke) ''The Archaeology of Memory'' (Oxford 2003) * (editor with John Cherry) ''Side-by-Side Survey: Comparative Regional Analysis in the Mediterranean Region'' (Oxford 2004) * (editor with Lauren Talalay) ''In the Field: The Archaeological Expeditions of the [[Kelsey Museum of Archaeology]]'' (Ann Arbor 2006)
